# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: comedy-in-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] The show was created by Tom Gutteridge (producer/director) and Sean Hardie (executive producer).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] Series One, comprising six shows, was broadcast on BBC2 from 21 September 1981 to 26 October 1981.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] Series Two, comprising four shows, was broadcast on BBC2 between 3 January 1984 and 24 January 1984.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] A contemporary sketch show with a nod to the then emerging wave of alternative comedy, a strong team combined to perform short sketches and various musical parodies.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] The show was the first break into television for Rik Mayall, who played an over-excited, anorak-wearing investigative reporter Kevin Turvey.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] To maintain the illusion that his character was real, Mayall's name did not appear in the closing credits whereas Kevin Turvey's did.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] The show was also an important early step in Tracey Ullman's television comedy career (along with Three of a Kind, first broadcast a few months before).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] Peter Capaldi, a trained graphic artist, contributed to designing the show's opening sequence prior to launching his own career as an actor.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] The first series won a Scottish BAFTA for Best Entertainment Programme in 1982.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] For the second series, Colin Gilbert was brought in as producer, his debut TV production with the newly formed BBC Scotland Comedy Unit.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] Richard Stilgoe had left the show and Robbie Coltrane took his place.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] This second series was more slick and competent than the first, and Coltrane was praised for his vocal range, powerful delivery and natural acting technique.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] A compilation episode was broadcast on 31 December 1987, entitled "A Kick Up The Bells".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/a-kick-up-the-eighties] On 31 December 1998 BBC2 screened "A Kick Up The Archive", a further highlights compilation.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The **Office of the Advocate General for Scotland** is a ministerial department of the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The position is currently occupied by Catherine Smith, Baroness Smith of Cluny.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of Advocate General for Scotland was created in 1999 by the Scotland Act 1998 to be the chief legal adviser to the United Kingdom Government on Scots law.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] This function had previously been carried out by the Lord Advocate and Solicitor General for Scotland, who were transferred to the Scottish Government on the establishment of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of the Advocate General for Scotland should not be confused with that of "His Majesty's Advocate", which is the term used for the Lord Advocate in Scottish criminal proceedings.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The first holder of the office was Lynda Clark, then Member of Parliament for Edinburgh Pentlands and from 2005 a member of the House of Lords as Baroness Clark of Calton.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 18 January 2006, Baroness Clark resigned to take up office as a Senator of the College of Justice, a judge of the Supreme Courts of Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office was then vacant until 15 March of that year when, under section 87 of the Scotland Act 1998, its functions were temporarily conferred on the Secretary of State for Scotland, Alistair Darling MP, himself a Scottish advocate.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] There had been substantial criticism from the judiciary and others of the length of time the office had been left vacant.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 21 March, however, it was announced Neil Davidson, former Solicitor General for Scotland, had been appointed Advocate General.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Davidson of Glen Clova, on 22 March 2006.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 14 May 2010, Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness, a former Deputy First Minister of Scotland, was appointed by the coalition government.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Richard Keen was appointed Advocate General in David Cameron's majority government on 29 May 2015, and has retained the post through two subsequent prime ministers to 2020.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Keen of Elie, on 8 June 2015.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He resigned on 16 September 2020 citing concerns arising from the UK Internal Market Bill, noting in his letter of resignation to Boris Johnson that he found it "increasingly difficult to reconcile what I consider to be my obligations as a Law Officer with your policy intentions".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Keith Stewart was appointed to succeed Keen on 15 October 2020.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Catherine Smith was appointed to the office and a life peerage by the Starmer government on 29 August 2024.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] All staff are on secondment or loan from other government organisations, mainly the Scottish Government and the Ministry of Justice.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early modern era saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The closing decade of the seventeenth century saw a slump, followed by four years of failed harvests, in what is known as the "seven ill years", but these shortages would be the last of their kind.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] After the Union of 1707 there was a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Introductions included haymaking, the English plough, new crops, crop rotation and encloses were introduced.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The resulting Lowland Clearances saw hundreds of thousands of cottars and tenant farmers from central and southern Scotland lose access to land and either become landless agricultural workers or emigrate to the growing industrial cities or elsewhere.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The later Highland Clearances involved the eviction of many traditional tenants as lands were enclosed, principally for sheep farming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the first phase, many Highlanders were relocated as crofters, living on very small rented farms which required other employment to be found.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the twentieth century Scottish agriculture became more susceptible to world markets.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There were dramatic price rises in the First World War, but a slump in the 1920s and 1930s, followed by more rises in World War II.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In 1947 annual price reviews were introduced in an attempt to stabilise the market.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was a drive in UK agriculture to greater production until the late 1970s, resulting in intensive farming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was increasing mechanisation and farming became less labour-intensive.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] UK membership of the European Economic Community from 1972 began a change in orientation for Scottish farming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some sectors became viable only with subsidies.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A series of reforms to the CAP from the 1990s attempted to control over-production, limit incentives for intensive farming and mitigate environmental damage.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A dual farm structure has emerged with agriculture divided between large commercial farms and small pluralised and diversified holdings.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Roughly 79 per cent of Scotland’s total land area is under agricultural production.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Cereals accounted for 78 per cent of cropped land area (not total farmed area), while livestock numbers have been falling in recent years.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Around 15 per cent of the total land area of Scotland is forested, most in public ownership controlled by the Forestry Commission.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Total income from farming has been rising since the turn of the millennium.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Aquaculture production is focused on the West and North of the country.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some farm businesses rely on sources of income other than from farming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scottish agriculture employs around 1.5 per cent of the workforce and contributes to around 1 per cent of the Scottish economy.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The defining factor in the geography of Scotland is the distinction between the Highlands and Islands in the north and west and the Lowlands in the south and east.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Highlands are further divided into the Northwest Highlands and the Grampian Mountains by the fault line of the Great Glen.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Lowlands are divided into the fertile belt of the Central Lowlands and the higher terrain of the Southern Uplands, which included the Cheviot Hills, over which the border with England runs.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Central Lowland belt averages about 50 miles in width, and contains most of the good quality agricultural land.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland is half the size of England and Wales in area, but with its many inlets, islands and inland lochs, it has roughly the same amount of coastline at 4,000 miles.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Only a fifth of Scotland is less than 60 metres above sea level.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland's soils are diverse for a relatively small country due to the variation in geology, topography, climate, altitude and land use history.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There are very productive arable soils in the east of the country, including some of the most productive for wheat and barley of anywhere in the world.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland's soils differ from much of the rest of the UK and Europe and they provide valuable habitats for wildlife and flora.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] They are largely naturally acidic in nature with high concentrations of organic carbon.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] They are predominantly coarse textured and often exhibit poor drainage.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The climate of Scotland is temperate and very changeable, but rarely extreme.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Scotland is warmed by the North Atlantic Drift and given the northerly location of the country, experiences much milder conditions than areas on similar latitudes.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Average temperatures are lower than in the rest of Great Britain.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Western coastal areas of Scotland are warmer than the east and inland areas, due to the influence of the Atlantic currents, and the colder surface temperatures of the North Sea.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Rainfall totals vary widely across Scotland—the western highlands of Scotland are one of the wettest places in the UK with annual rainfall up to 4,577 mm (180.2 in).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In comparison, much of eastern Scotland receives less than 870 mm (34.3 in) annually; lying in the rain shadow of the western uplands.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Annual average sunshine totals vary from as little as 711–1140 hours in the Highlands and the north-west up to 1471–1540 hours on the extreme eastern and south-western coasts.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Wind prevails from the south-west, bringing warm, wet and unstable air from the Atlantic.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The windiest areas of Scotland are in the north and west, with parts of the Outer Hebrides, Orkney and Shetland experiencing over 30 days with gales per year.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Vigorous Atlantic depressions, also known as European windstorms, are a common feature of the autumn and winter in Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Mesolithic hunter-gatherer encampments formed the first known settlements in Scotland around 8500 BCE.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] These were highly mobile boat-using people making tools from bone, stone and antlers.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the Neolithic period, around 6,000 years ago, there is evidence of permanent settlements and farming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Archaeological evidence indicates that the two main sources of food were grain and cow's milk.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] From the beginning of the Bronze Age, about 2000 BCE, arable land spread at the expense of forest.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] From the Iron Age, beginning in the seventh century BCE, there is evidence of hill forts in southern Scotland that are associated with cultivation ridges and terraces.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Souterrains, small underground constructions, may have been for storing perishable agricultural products.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Aerial photography reveals extensive prehistoric field systems that underlie existing boundaries in some Lowland areas, suggesting that the fertile plains were already densely exploited for agriculture.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] During the period of Roman occupation there was re-growth of birch, oak and hazel for five centuries, suggesting a decline of population and agriculture.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early Middle Ages were a period of climate deterioration resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Farming was based around a single homestead or a small cluster of three or four homes, each probably containing a nuclear family.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than corn (here meaning wheat) and cattle were the most important domesticated animal.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] As feudal distinctions declined in the early modern era, the barons and tenants-in-chief merged to form a new identifiable group, the lairds.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] With the substantial landholders of the yeomen, these heritors were the major landholding orders.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Those with property rights included husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Many young people, both male and female, left home to become domestic and agricultural servants.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The early modern era also saw the impact of the Little Ice Age, of colder and wetter weather, which peaked towards the end of the seventeenth century.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Almost half the years in the second half of the sixteenth century saw local or national scarcity, necessitating the shipping of large quantities of grain from the Baltic.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the early seventeenth century famine was relatively common, with four periods of famine prices between 1620 and 1625.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The English invasions of the 1640s had a profound impact on the Scottish economy.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Under the Commonwealth, the country was relatively highly taxed, but gained access to English markets.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] After the Restoration the formal frontier with England was re-established, along with its customs duties.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Economic conditions were generally favourable from 1660 to 1688, as land owners promoted better tillage and cattle-raising.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The closing decade of the seventeenth century there was a slump in trade with the Baltic and France and changes in the Scottish cattle trade, followed by four years of failed harvests (1695, 1696 and 1698-9), known as the "seven ill years".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The shortages of the 1690s would be the last of their kind.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Increasing contacts with England after the Union of 1707 led to a conscious attempt to improve agriculture among the gentry and nobility.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The English plough was introduced and foreign grasses, the sowing of rye grass and clover.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Turnips and cabbages were introduced, lands enclosed and marshes drained, lime was put down to combat soil acidity, roads built and woods planted.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Drilling and sowing and crop rotation were introduced.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The introduction of the potato to Scotland in 1739 provided a crop with a high yield, producing 3 to 5 times more calories per acre than a cereal crop.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Enclosures began to displace the run rig system.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The first result of these changes were the Lowland Clearances.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The botanist John Hope complained about British naturalists who were enthusiastically exploring the landscape of colonial America while "absolutely inattentive to the natural productions of our native country".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] He founded the Society for the Importation of Foreign Seeds and Plants pursuing, as Carl Linnaeus did in Lapland, the adaptation of valuable cash crop plants to the Highlands.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Agricultural improvement spread north and west, mostly over the period 1760 to 1850 as the Highland Clearances.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Many farming tenants were evicted and offered tenancies in crofting communities, with their former possessions converted into large-scale sheep farms.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Crofts were intended to be too small to support the occupants, so forcing them to work in other industries, such as fishing, quarrying or kelping.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the 1840 and 1850s Scotland suffered its last major subsistence crisis, when the potato blight that caused the Great Famine of Ireland reached the Highlands in 1846.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] This gave rise to the second phase of the Highland clearances, when landlords provided assisted passages for their tenants to emigrate in a desperate effort to rid themselves of a redundant population that was dependent on famine relief.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the twentieth century Scottish agriculture became susceptible to the ups and downs of world markets.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] After World War II there was a drive in UK agriculture to greater production until the late 1970s, resulting in intensive farming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] More areas of marginal land were brought into production.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was increasing mechanisation of Scottish agriculture and farming became less labour-intensive.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The UK membership of the European Economic Community (later the European Union) in 1972 began a change in orientation for Scottish farming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some sectors, particularly hill sheep farming, became viable only with subsidies.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A dual farm structure emerged, with agriculture divided between large commercial farms and small pluralised and diversified holdings.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] At the time of the June 2013 agricultural census the total area of agricultural holdings in Scotland was 5.6 million hectares, equal to 73 per cent of Scotland’s total land area.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Just over half of this was rough grazing, with about a quarter taken up by grass, and about ten per cent used for crops or left fallow.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The remainder was made up of woodland, ponds, yards or other uses.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] There was a further 580,000 hectares of common grazing, which if included made the total area 6.2 million hectares, or 79 per cent of Scotland’s total land area.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Because of the persistence of feudalism and the land enclosures of the nineteenth century, the ownership of most land is concentrated in relatively few hands (some 350 people own about half the land).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] As a result, in 2003 the Scottish Parliament passed Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 that empowered tenant farmers and communities to purchase land even if the landlord did not want to sell.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In June 2013, of crops grown in Scotland (excluding grass), cereals accounted for 78 per cent of the land area, with nearly three-quarters of that being barley (340,000 hectares).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Wheat was also significant (87,000 hectares), along with oilseed rape (34,000 hectares), oats (32,000 hectares) and potatoes (29,000 hectares).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Amongst fruit and vegetables, a total of 911 hectares of strawberries were grown, mainly under cover, which was the largest source of income amongst horticulture crops.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The major areas of cereal production were Grampian, Tayside, Borders, Lothian and Fife.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Livestock numbers have been falling in recent years.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The trend began at the turn of the millennium in the case of pigs and sheep and dates to the mid-1970s in the case of cattle.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In June 2013 there were 6.6 million sheep, 1.8 million cattle and 308,000 pigs, the lowest numbers since the 1940 and 1950s.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Poultry numbers have tended to fluctuate over the last 25 years, but were down to 14.2 million in 2013.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] About 13,340 km2 of land in Scotland is forested representing around 15 per cent of the total land area of Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The majority of forests are in public ownership, with forestry policy being controlled by the Forestry Commission.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The biggest plantations and timber resources are to be found in Dumfries and Galloway, Tayside, Argyll and the area governed by Highland Council.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The economic activities generated by forestry in Scotland include planting and harvesting as well as sawmilling, the production of pulp and paper and the manufacture of higher value goods.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Forests, especially those surrounding populated areas in Central Scotland also provide a recreation resource.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Total income from farming (TIFF) has been rising since the turn of the millennium.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] It was estimated at £700 million in 2012, being made up of £2.9 billion in outputs and £570 million in support payments, offset by £2.8 billion in costs.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The initial estimate of TIFF for 2013 was £830 million, an increase largely linked to the improved weather.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] TIFF per annual work unit increased to £31,000, similar to the value in 2011.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The total output of aquaculture was estimated in 2011 at around £434 million per year, including around £412 million for farmed Atlantic salmon, £14.34 million for rainbow trout and £7.7 million for shellfish.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Brown trout, sea trout, halibut and Arctic charr are also farmed in Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Some farm businesses rely on sources of income other than from farming, including contracting work, hosting mobile phone masts, tourism and recreation and financial support from grants and subsidies.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Analysis of the Farm Accounts Survey suggests that, excluding support from grants and subsidies, the average farm made a loss of £16,000 in 2012.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] However, calculations from TIFF suggest that, excluding support, the sector still made a small profit.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Government figures indicate that in 2013 Scottish agriculture employed around 1.5 per cent of the workforce and contributes around 1 per cent of the Scottish economy.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In the Highlands and Islands, around 10 per cent of the workforce are engaged in agriculture and livestock products contribute around 70 per cent of the output.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The West of Scotland Agricultural College formed in 1899, the East of Scotland Agricultural College in 1901, and the North of Scotland Agricultural College in 1904; these colleges amalgamated to form the Scottish Agricultural College in 1990.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Site-specific nature conservations began in the UK with the creation of the Nature Conservancy in 1948, which later became the Nature Conservancy Council (NCC).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] It moved from a research-based advisory group to become a campaigning body.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The 1949 National Parks and Access to the Countryside Act excluded Scotland, but introduced the concept of Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI), which were to become a key part of managing nature conservation.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] A Countryside Commission Scotland (CSS) was established under the Countryside Scotland Act, 1967.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The NCC was broken up in 1991 and in Scotland was merged with CSS to produce Scottish Natural Heritage (SNH), under a UK-wide Joint Nature Conservation Committee.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] SNH has a remit for both land and nature conservation and a responsibility towards sustainability and to the consideration of the needs of the Scottish people.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] In Scotland, a right of way is a route over which the public has been able to pass unhindered for at least 20 years.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The route must link two "public places", such as villages, churches or roads.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Unlike in England and Wales there is no obligation on Scottish local authorities to signpost or mark a right of way.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] However, the charity Scotways, formed in 1845 to protect rights of way, records and signs the routes.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] The Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 gives everyone statutory access rights to most land and inland water in Scotland, to non-motorized traffic, making the existence of rights of way less important in terms of access to land in Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/agriculture-in-scotland] Certain categories of land are excluded from this presumption of open access, such as railway land, airfields and private gardens.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] On 20 June 2017, the Air Departure Tax (Scotland) Act 2017 was passed in the Scottish Parliament and received royal assent on 25 July 2017 and was meant to be introduced on 1 April 2018.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] However, on 22 November 2017, the UK and Scottish ministers agreed to delay the introduction of ADT until issues have been resolved regarding the tax exemption for flights departing airports in the Highlands and Islands of Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] In June 2018, the Scottish Government and UK Government agreed that it would not be possible to introduce the ADT in April 2019.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] Air Passenger Duty has continued to apply for airports in Scotland and HMRC has continued to administer APD in relation to flights in Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] On 13 January 2026, it was announced that an alternative to maintain an exemption for the Highlands and Islands from the tax had been designed.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] The tax will now apply from 1 April 2027.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] The Scottish Government intended to reduce the rate by 50%, and eventually abolish it completely once finances allowed.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] This caused concern that such a move could damage tourism in England.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/air-departure-tax] However, in 2019 the Scottish Government abandoned its plans to cut Air Departure Tax as the proposals were no longer considered compatible with Scotland's climate change targets.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He is also known for his roles as Fegan Floop in the *Spy Kids* trilogy (2001–2003), Nightcrawler in *X2* (2003), and Loki in *Son of the Mask* (2005).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] On television, Cumming is best known for his role in the CBS series *The Good Wife* (2010–2016), for which he was nominated for three Primetime Emmy Awards, two Screen Actors Guild Awards, and two Golden Globe Awards.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming also starred in the CBS series *Instinct* (2018–2019), the Apple TV+ series *Schmigadoon!* (2021–2023) and is the host of the Peacock reality game show *The Traitors*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming has written a novel, *Tommy's Tale* (2002), and two memoirs, published in 2014 and 2019.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming was born on 27 January 1965 in Aberfeldy, Perthshire, Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] His mother, Mary Darling, was an insurance company secretary and his father, Alex Cumming, was the head forester of Panmure Estate, which is located near Carnoustie, on the east coast of Scotland, and is where Cumming grew up.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He has described the environment as "feudal".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He has a brother, Tom, who is six years older, and a niece and two nephews.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming attended Monikie Primary School and Carnoustie High School.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In his autobiography *Not My Father's Son*, Cumming describes the emotional and physical violence his father inflicted on him in his childhood.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] His mother found it impossible to obtain a divorce until she was financially independent.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming said that, after his early 20s, he did not have any communication with his father until just before the filming of his episode of the series *Who Do You Think You Are?* He then found out his father had believed that Cumming was not his biological son.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Later, Cumming and his brother took DNA tests that proved they were indeed his biological children.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming said that his difficult childhood taught him how to act by "needing to suppress my own emotions and feelings around him [his father] when I was a little boy".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He has described himself as having been a voracious reader as a child, particularly of *The Famous Five* series by Enid Blyton.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 1984, Cumming made his television debut in ITV Granada's *Travelling Man*, before going on to appear later in the 1980s in the Scottish Television series *Take the High Road*, *Taggart* and *Shadow of the Stone*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming made his film debut in Gillies MacKinnon's short film *Passing Glory* in 1986.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] His breakthrough television role was as Bernard Bottle in the Christmas 1991 BBC comedy *Bernard and the Genie*, a Richard Curtis-scripted film in which he starred alongside Lenny Henry and Rowan Atkinson.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He also featured in a comic relief sketch in 1993 on the popular UK television show *Blind Date* with Atkinson playing Mr.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] After graduating from the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama, Cumming joined with fellow graduate Forbes Masson to form the comedy duo Victor and Barry, appearing at the 1984 Edinburgh Fringe and presenting television shows.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In the 1990s, their popular characters were later reinvented as Steve and Sebastian for *The High Life* television series.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] The series was written by Cumming and Masson.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 1995, Cumming appeared in the series *Ghosts*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] His feature film debut came in 1992 when he starred alongside Sandrine Bonnaire and Bruno Ganz in Ian Sellar's *Prague*, which premiered at the Cannes Film Festival and earned him the Best Actor award at the Atlantic Film Festival and a Scottish BAFTA Best Actor nomination.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] American audiences first saw him portraying the smarmy Sean Walsh, an unwanted suitor of Minnie Driver's character, in *Circle of Friends*, an Irish film released in 1995.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Also, in 1995, he played Boris Ivanovich Grishenko in the James Bond film *GoldenEye*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming began his theatre career in his native Scotland, performing in seasons with the Royal Lyceum Edinburgh, Dundee Rep, The Tron Glasgow and tours with Borderline, Theatre Workshop and Glasgow Citizens' TAG.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He played Slupianek in the Traverse Theatre's 1988 production of *Conquest of the South Pole*, which later transferred to the Royal Court in London and earned him an Olivier Award nomination as Most Promising Newcomer.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He went on to perform plays with the Bristol Old Vic and the Royal Shakespeare Company and played Valere in *La Bete* at the Lyric Hammersmith, London.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 1991, he played The Madman in the 1990 Royal National Theatre production of *Accidental Death of an Anarchist* by Dario Fo, for which he won the Laurence Olivier Award for Best Comedy Performance.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He also adapted the play with director Tim Supple.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 1993, he received great critical acclaim and the TMA Best Actor award for playing the title role in the 1993 English Touring Theatre's *Hamlet* (playing opposite his then-wife, Hilary Lyon, in the role of Ophelia).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He gained prominence for his role as The Master of Ceremonies in Sam Mendes's 1993 revival of the musical *Cabaret* in London's West End opposite Jane Horrocks as Sally Bowles.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He received an Olivier Award nomination for Best Actor in a Musical.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He reprised the role in 1998 for the Mendes-Rob Marshall Broadway revival, this time opposite Natasha Richardson as Sally Bowles.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He won a Tony Award, Drama Desk Award and Outer Critics Circle Award for his performance.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming had a minor role in Stanley Kubrick's final film, *Eyes Wide Shut* (1999), as a hotel clerk who humorously flirts with Tom Cruise's character; according to Cumming, he was required to go through six auditions for the role.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] His first film in the United States was 1997's *Romy and Michele's High School Reunion*, playing Sandy Frink opposite Lisa Kudrow and Mira Sorvino.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming co-wrote, co-directed, co-produced and co-starred in the ensemble film *The Anniversary Party* with friend and former *Cabaret* co-star Jennifer Jason Leigh in 2001.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Other US stage roles include Otto in the 2001 Broadway production of *Design for Living* by Noël Coward and Mack the Knife in the Bertolt Brecht-Kurt Weill musical *The Threepenny Opera* opposite Cyndi Lauper.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming performed alongside Dianne Wiest in Classic Stage Company's production of Anton Chekhov's *The Seagull*, directed by Viacheslav Dolgachev.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2002, Cumming and then-boyfriend Nick Philippou formed the production company The Art Party.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] The company's first and only play was the first English production of Jean Genet's play *Elle*, which Cumming had adapted from a literal translation by Terri Gordon.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming's novel, *Tommy's Tale*, was published in 2002.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He has also written articles for magazines, notably as a contributing editor for *Marie Claire*, writing on the haute couture shows in Paris, as well as what it was like for him dressing as a woman for a day.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He also contributed articles to *Newsweek*, *Modern Painters*, *Out*, *Black Book* and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He has written introductions and prefaces to various books, including the works of Nancy Mitford, Andy Warhol and Christopher Isherwood, and wrote a chapter of *If You Had Five Minutes with the President*, a collection of 55+ essays by members or supporters of The Creative Coalition.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2006, he returned to the West End playing the lead role in *Bent*, a play about homosexuals in Germany under the Nazis.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming introduced *Masterpiece Mystery!* for PBS, beginning in 2008.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He played Eli Gold on the CBS television show *The Good Wife*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He appeared as a guest star in the latter third of the first season, becoming a series regular in the show's 2010–2011 season.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] On 1 September 2009, Cumming released his first solo album based around his one-man show, *I Bought a Blue Car Today*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming returned to British television screens in 2011 to star as Desrae, a crossdresser, on the Sky series *The Runaway*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He collaborated again with Tiffany and the National Theatre of Scotland in 2012, playing all the roles in *Macbeth*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He brought this critically acclaimed production of *Macbeth*to New York's Lincoln Center in 2012 and to a 73-show Broadway engagement at the Ethel Barrymore Theatre in 2013.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] *Macbeth* concluded its run on Broadway on 14 July 2013.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2012, he narrated the audiobook *Macbeth: A Novel*, written by A.J.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] The novel greatly expands upon the themes established in the play.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] On 10 April 2012, he released the single "Someone Like the Edge of Firework".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2012, he launched his photography career with his first exhibition Alan Cumming Snaps.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In July 2012, Cumming presented *Urban Secrets* on Sky Atlantic and the Travel Channel where he uncovers hidden secrets in various urban areas including London and Brighton.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In October 2013, Cumming appeared in the music video for "City of Angels" by Thirty Seconds to Mars.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2014, he published his autobiography, *Not My Father's Son*, which deals with both his experiences growing up with an abusive father and the discoveries he made about his maternal grandfather's life while filming *Who Do You Think You Are?*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] That same year he returned again to Broadway to star in Roundabout Theater Company's revival production of *Cabaret*, directed again by Sam Mendes.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Starring opposite Michelle Williams, *Cabaret* opened 24 April 2014 and closed 29 March 2015.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] The run was extended originally from its 24-week engagement.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] The role of Sally changed during the production, when Williams left, to include Emma Stone and Sienna Miller.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] On 7 June 2015, Cumming co-hosted the 69th annual Tony Awards alongside Kristin Chenoweth.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] On 5 February 2016, Cumming released his second full-length album, recorded live at New York City's Café Carlyle, *Alan Cumming Sings Sappy Songs: Live at the Cafe Carlyle*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He toured an aptly styled, intimate, cabaret-like live stage production following his success with the Carlyle recording.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In November 2016, PBS aired a filming of his show *Alan Cumming Sings Sappy Songs* from The Smith Center in Las Vegas.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2016, NBC's *1st Look* visited Scotland for a special episode, featuring Alan Cumming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] It featured areas of the country that are important to Cumming, and showcased Scotland through his eyes.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] The show was named Best Lifestyle Programme at the Emmys' 60th annual awards ceremony at New York's Marriott Marquis Broadway Ballroom.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Alan Cumming was cast as the lead character in the CBS series *Instinct*, an academic seeking to help the NYPD solve crimes.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2018, he played King James on the eleventh series of *Doctor Who*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In September 2017, Cumming and promoter Daniel Nardicio opened a bar in Manhattan's East Village called Club Cumming.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Starting in 2022, Cumming partnered with British-Australian actress Miriam Margolyes in a television series entitled *Miriam and Alan: Lost in Scotland*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] The series follows the pair as they travel in a motorhome and explore Scotland.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] That same year, Cumming appeared in *My Old School*, a documentary about the case of Brandon Lee, a 32-year-old man exposed in 1995 as having attended a Scottish secondary school in the guise of a 17-year-old.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming appeared as an avatar for Lee, who did not want to appear on camera for the film, lip syncing to audio of his interviews.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming had previously planned to play Lee in a theatrical production in the late 90s which failed to materialize.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In June 2021, Cumming was artistic director of the Adelaide Cabaret Festival, as announced in June 2020.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Later that year, he played Mayor Aloysius Menlove, the closeted small-town mayor of Schmigadoon, in the Apple TV+ comedy musical series *Schmigadoon!* Since 2023, Cumming hosts the American version of the reality TV series *The Traitors*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2025, he hosted the first episode of CNN's *My Happy Place* talking about his connection to the Scottish Highlands and featuring his attendance at the Gordon Castle Highland games.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming joined Pitlochry Festival Theatre as artistic director in January 2025, with his programmed season beginning in 2026.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Later that year, Cumming starred in the short film *Sleazy Tiger*, written and directed by award-winning Scottish writer James Ley, which had its world premiere at Palm Springs International Film Festival ShortFest, as part of the GAYLA! programme.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] It also starred Jay Newton and Jack Douglas.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In July 2025, he was a guest host on *Jimmy Kimmel Live*, when he criticised the US government and President Donald Trump over LGBT issues and trans rights.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In June 2025, Cumming voiced the character The Haberdasher in season five of the Disney Channel cartoon, *Phineas and Ferb.* The eighth episode aired on 6 June 2025, and featured the character.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He produced the Baltimore run of *Ceilidh*, a musical based on the Scottish cèilidh tradition written by Scott Gilmour and Claire McKenzie, and directed and choreographed by Tony winner Sam Pinkleton.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He will star opposite Gaten Matarazzo, Bebe Neuwirth, and a full cast in the Audible Original *Underdogs: A Musical*, set to release March 2026.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming is set to reprise his role as Nightcrawler from *X2* in the Marvel Cinematic Universe film *Avengers: Doomsday* (2026).
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming also supports several AIDS charities, including the American Foundation for AIDS Research (AMFAR) and Broadway Cares/Equity Fights AIDS.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2005, he released an award-winning fragrance called "Cumming" and a related line of scented bath lotion and body wash.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] A second fragrance was launched in 2011, named "Second (Alan) Cumming", with all proceeds going to charity.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He is a supporter of the Scottish National Party and Scottish independence.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He supported the 'Yes' campaign in the run-up to Scotland's referendum on independence in September 2014.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In October 2014, Cumming and the Broadway cast of *Cabaret* collected donations for Broadway Cares/Equity Fights AIDS.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming endorsed Senator Bernie Sanders in the 2016 US presidential election.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In October 2023, he signed the Artists4Ceasefire open letter to American President Joe Biden that called for a ceasefire of the Israeli bombardment of Gaza.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] His relationships include an eight-year marriage to actress Hilary Lyon, a two-year relationship with actress Saffron Burrows, and a six-year relationship with theatre director Nick Philippou.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2006, Cumming stated that he "would dearly like to adopt a child", but that his life was "too hectic" for the rearing of children.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming and his husband, illustrator Grant Shaffer, dated for two years before becoming civil partners at the Old Royal Naval College in Greenwich, London, on 7 January 2007.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming and Shaffer legally married in New York on 7 January 2012, the fifth anniversary of their London union.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] On 7 November 2008, Cumming became a dual-national and was sworn in as a citizen of the United States at a ceremony in Manhattan.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming has stated that since 2012 he has maintained a vegan lifestyle.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] PETA awarded him its Humanitarian Award in 2017.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In March 2005, Cumming received the Vito Russo Award at the 16th Annual GLAAD Media Awards for outstanding contributions toward eliminating homophobia.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In July of the same year, he was presented with the HRC's Humanitarian Award in San Francisco, also for his LGBT public stance.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In November 2006, Cumming received a Doctor of Arts honorary degree from the University of Abertay Dundee, and in 2015 he received an honorary degree from the Open University.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] He also is a patron of the Scottish Youth Theatre, Scotland's National Theatre "for and by" young people.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming was appointed Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) in the 2009 Birthday Honours for services to film, theatre and the arts and to activism for equal rights for the gay and lesbian community in the United States.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] On 27 January 2023, his 58th birthday, Cumming announced via his Instagram page that he had decided to return his OBE due to "misgivings I have being associated with the toxicity of empire".
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] Cumming has also been honoured for his activism and humanitarian work by organisations such as the Trevor Project and the Matthew Shepard Foundation.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2022, he received a Tony Award for Best Musical as a producer of the musical *A Strange Loop*.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In 2025, Cumming was awarded a law doctorate by the University of St Andrews in recognition of his service to the arts.
[src:comedy-in-scotland/alan-cumming] In January 2026 he was honoured with a star on Hollywood Walk of Fame.
